explanation:
To decide if OS_API_Teardown contains unreachable code you must know whether any of the called routines can fail to return (exit the process, loop forever, block indefinitely, longjmp out, or otherwise prevent subsequent calls from executing). The listed symbols are required for that analysis:

- OS_DeleteAllObjects: direct first callee; if it does not return (e.g. blocks forever or calls exit/longjmp) then the subsequent OS_ApplicationShutdown call would be unreachable.
- OS_ForEachObject / OS_ForEachObjectOfType: used by OS_DeleteAllObjects (per call graph). Their behavior (iterate-and-return vs. infinite loop/blocked wait) affects whether OS_DeleteAllObjects returns.
- OS_TaskDelay: called by OS_DeleteAllObjects (per graph); may cause indefinite blocking or repeated sleeps that make progress impossible — relevant to reachability of later code.
- OS_ApplicationShutdown: direct second callee; if it does not return (e.g. terminates the application) that affects whether any code after it would be unreachable and whether earlier statements could be considered pointless.
- OS_ApplicationShutdown_Impl: implementation called by OS_ApplicationShutdown (per graph); must be inspected for non-returning behavior (exit, infinite loop, longjmp, thread termination semantics).
- UT_ExecuteBasicHandler: appears in the call graph for both OS_DeleteAllObjects and OS_ApplicationShutdown (and their subcalls); this test/stub dispatcher can install/execute handlers that may change control flow (including non-returning handlers) so its behavior is required to determine reachability.
- UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData / UT_GetStubEntry / UT_SetHandlerFunction / UT_DefaultStubImpl: internals used by UT_ExecuteBasicHandler (per graph). They can register or invoke test stub handlers which could replace normal behavior with non-returning handlers or handlers that longjmp; therefore their semantics are needed to decide if calls return.

Inspecting the bodies of these symbols will reveal whether any call in OS_API_Teardown can be non-returning or block indefinitely and thus whether any subsequent statement becomes unreachable (MISRA: no unreachable code).
